Note:
UNITS_OF_MEDASURE - Tier 1 dimensional analysis for the Runa stdlib

This file implements compile-time dimensional analysis through nominal typing.
Each physical quantity (Length, Mass, Time, etc.) is a DISTINCT type wrapping
a Float64 SI base value. Because Runa's type system is nominal, a procedure
declared as taking `Length` will refuse a `Mass` value even though both wrap
a Float internally. Cross-dimensional addition (length + time) is rejected
at compile time. Cross-dimensional multiplication (length * length -> area)
is expressed via separate constructor procedures that consume two typed
quantities and yield a typed product.

WHY THIS MATTERS

The Mars Climate Orbiter (NASA, 1999) was lost because the ground-based
navigation software produced impulse values in pound-force seconds (lbf*s)
while the on-board software expected newton-seconds (N*s). The mismatch was
a 4.45x scale factor on every thruster firing. A 327M USD spacecraft burned
up in the Martian atmosphere because the unit boundary was implicit, not
typed. F# units of measure and the Frink language have since shown that
making dimensions a first-class type system property eliminates this entire
bug class.

Engineering-grade unit safety is non-negotiable for production aerospace,
robotics, and physics-simulation code.

REPRESENTATION

Each quantity is stored as an SI base value in a Float field. Conversions to
and from common engineering units (km, mile, ft, etc.) are EXPLICIT through
named constructors and accessors. There is no implicit conversion: users who
want to add a length given in feet to a length given in meters must invoke
the conversion procedure, which makes the unit boundary visible in the code
and reviewable by humans.

DESIGN CHOICES

1. Float (binary64) for the storage type. Adequate for ~15.95 decimal digits,
   matches engineering practice. For higher precision (orbit-class problems)
   a future units_extended_precision.runa may add Float128-backed variants.

2. Distinct nominal types per quantity. No generic parameter on a single
   Quantity[D] because stage1 has no generics. The resulting code is more
   verbose but provides identical compile-time guarantees and is fully
   transparent to the type checker.

3. Conversions enumerate the common engineering units. The base unit of
   each quantity is the SI base unit (meter for length, kilogram for mass,
   second for time, kelvin for temperature, ampere for current, mole for
   substance, candela for luminous intensity, radian for angle).

4. Derived quantities (velocity, force, energy, ...) each get their own
   type and are constructed by multiplying or dividing other typed
   quantities. The constructor procedure (e.g. velocity_from_length_and_time)
   makes the dimensional combination explicit and audit-friendly.

5. Temperature is special: kelvin and rankine are absolute scales (zero is
   absolute zero) so they participate in ratios; celsius and fahrenheit
   are interval scales (zero is arbitrary) so only differences are
   well-defined ratios. The to/from-celsius and to/from-fahrenheit
   procedures perform the offset transformation; users wanting to add two
   celsius temperatures should convert to kelvin first.

EXPORTED TYPES (one per quantity)

  Base SI quantities (7 from BIPM SI brochure 9th edition, 2019):
    Length, Mass, Time, Temperature, ElectricCurrent,
    AmountOfSubstance, LuminousIntensity

  Plane geometry:
    Angle

  Derived mechanical quantities:
    Area, Volume, Velocity, Acceleration, Jerk,
    Force, Pressure, Energy, Power, Torque

  Derived electromagnetic quantities:
    Voltage, Resistance, Capacitance, Inductance, Charge

  Derived rotational and oscillatory quantities:
    AngularVelocity, AngularAcceleration, Frequency

  Information theory and data:
    Information, DataRate

EXPORTED CONSTRUCTORS (one per common engineering unit)

  Length: length_in_meters, length_in_kilometers, length_in_centimeters,
          length_in_millimeters, length_in_miles, length_in_feet,
          length_in_inches, length_in_yards, length_in_astronomical_units,
          length_in_light_years, length_in_parsecs

  Mass: mass_in_kilograms, mass_in_grams, mass_in_pounds, mass_in_slugs,
        mass_in_solar_masses, mass_in_planck_masses

  Time: time_in_seconds, time_in_milliseconds, time_in_microseconds,
        time_in_nanoseconds, time_in_picoseconds, time_in_femtoseconds

  ... (see procedure declarations below for the full list)

EXPORTED ACCESSORS (one per common engineering unit)

  Length: length_to_meters, length_to_kilometers, length_to_miles, ...
  ... (see procedure declarations below)

EXPORTED OPERATIONS

  Same-dimension addition: length_add(a as Length, b as Length) -> Length
  Same-dimension subtraction: length_subtract
  Scalar multiplication: length_scale(l as Length, s as Float) -> Length
  Scalar division: length_divide_scalar(l as Length, s as Float) -> Length

  Cross-dimension multiplication (typed product):
    velocity_from_length_and_time(l, t) -> Velocity
    area_from_length_length(a, b)        -> Area
    force_from_mass_acceleration(m, a)   -> Force
    energy_from_force_length(f, d)       -> Energy
    power_from_energy_time(e, t)         -> Power
    ... and so on

  Same-dimension comparison: length_equals, length_less_than,
  length_greater_than (compare SI base values).

CITATIONS

  - NIST SP 811 (2008): Guide for the Use of the International System of
    Units. Section 4 (SI prefixes), Tables 6-9 (derived units).
  - BIPM SI Brochure 9th Edition (2019). The seven base units redefined
    in terms of fundamental constants.
  - NASA Mars Climate Orbiter Mishap Investigation Board Phase I Report
    (1999-11-10). Root cause: ground-software thrust output in lbf*s,
    flight-software input expecting N*s.
  - IEC 60027-2:2019 (binary prefixes kibi-, mebi-, gibi-, ...)
  - IEEE 754-2019 binary64 floating point format used as backing storage.

DEPENDENCIES

  - compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa for sqrt where
    energy-from-mass-velocity-squared style derivations call it. Direct
    Float arithmetic uses the language operators (plus, minus, multiplied
    by, divided by) which lower to SSE2 instructions in the stage1 backend.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Arith

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1 - Base SI quantity types
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "Length":
    si_meters as Float
End Type

Type called "Mass":
    si_kilograms as Float
End Type

Type called "Time":
    si_seconds as Float
End Type

Type called "Temperature":
    si_kelvin as Float
End Type

Type called "ElectricCurrent":
    si_amperes as Float
End Type

Type called "AmountOfSubstance":
    si_moles as Float
End Type

Type called "LuminousIntensity":
    si_candela as Float
End Type

Type called "Angle":
    si_radians as Float
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2 - Derived mechanical quantity types
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "Area":
    si_square_meters as Float
End Type

Type called "Volume":
    si_cubic_meters as Float
End Type

Type called "Velocity":
    si_meters_per_second as Float
End Type

Type called "Acceleration":
    si_meters_per_second_squared as Float
End Type

Type called "Jerk":
    si_meters_per_second_cubed as Float
End Type

Type called "Force":
    si_newtons as Float
End Type

Type called "Pressure":
    si_pascals as Float
End Type

Type called "Energy":
    si_joules as Float
End Type

Type called "Power":
    si_watts as Float
End Type

Type called "Torque":
    si_newton_meters as Float
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3 - Derived electromagnetic quantity types
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "Voltage":
    si_volts as Float
End Type

Type called "Resistance":
    si_ohms as Float
End Type

Type called "Capacitance":
    si_farads as Float
End Type

Type called "Inductance":
    si_henries as Float
End Type

Type called "Charge":
    si_coulombs as Float
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4 - Derived rotational and oscillatory quantity types
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "AngularVelocity":
    si_radians_per_second as Float
End Type

Type called "AngularAcceleration":
    si_radians_per_second_squared as Float
End Type

Type called "Frequency":
    si_hertz as Float
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5 - Information and data rate types
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "Information":
    si_bits as Float
End Type

Type called "DataRate":
    si_bits_per_second as Float
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 6 - Length: constructors and accessors
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Conversion factors:
Note:   1 km     = 1000 m
Note:   1 cm     = 0.01 m
Note:   1 mm     = 0.001 m
Note:   1 mile   = 1609.344 m (exact, international mile)
Note:   1 ft     = 0.3048 m (exact, international foot)
Note:   1 in     = 0.0254 m (exact, international inch)
Note:   1 yd     = 0.9144 m (exact, international yard)
Note:   1 AU     = 149597870700 m (IAU 2012 definition, exact)
Note:   1 ly     = 9460730472580800 m (Julian year, exact by IAU)
Note:   1 pc     = 3.0856775814913673e16 m (parsec, IAU 2015)

Process called "length_in_meters" takes value as Float returns Length:
    @Reasoning:
        Canonical constructor for Length. The meter is the SI base unit for
        length and so requires no scale factor. All other length constructors
        funnel through their own scale-and-store and produce a Length whose
        si_meters field is the value in SI meters. Returning a typed Length
        rather than a bare Float closes the dimensional analysis loop -
        downstream procedures that accept Length will reject any Float that
        was not produced by one of these constructors.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Construct a default-initialized Length and write the input value into
        the si_meters field. No range check is performed; negative lengths are
        permitted because callers may legitimately represent signed
        displacements (e.g. components of a position vector).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Single store. Compiles to one MOVSD on x86-64 and one STR on ARM64.
        No allocation, no branching, no dependency on the runtime.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure function. No I/O, no shared state, no memory allocation. Cannot
        fail. Caller-supplied Float is stored verbatim; if the caller is
        adversarial they can produce NaN or infinity, which will propagate
        through subsequent dimensional arithmetic per IEEE 754 semantics.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l be a value of type Length
    Set l.si_meters to value
    Return l
End Process

Process called "length_in_kilometers" takes value as Float returns Length:
    @Reasoning:
        Convert kilometers to SI meters by multiplying by 10^3. Kilometers are
        the most common engineering length unit outside metric-base contexts
        and so receive a dedicated constructor rather than forcing callers to
        compute the conversion themselves.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Multiply by 1000.0 and store in si_meters. The factor is exact in
        binary64 because 1000 = 10^3 = 2^3 * 5^3 and the 5^3 component (125)
        is small enough that the product is representable.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One MULSD, one MOVSD on x86-64. No allocator interaction.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Subject to the same NaN/infinity propagation as the other
        constructors.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l be a value of type Length
    Set l.si_meters to value multiplied by 1000.0
    Return l
End Process

Process called "length_in_centimeters" takes value as Float returns Length:
    Let l be a value of type Length
    Set l.si_meters to value multiplied by 0.01
    Return l
End Process

Process called "length_in_millimeters" takes value as Float returns Length:
    Let l be a value of type Length
    Set l.si_meters to value multiplied by 0.001
    Return l
End Process

Process called "length_in_miles" takes value as Float returns Length:
    @Reasoning:
        The international mile is defined as exactly 1609.344 m per the 1959
        international yard agreement (signed by the United States, the United
        Kingdom, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, and South Africa). The
        US survey mile (1609.347... m) differs in the sixth decimal and is
        used only in legacy cadastral data; we do not provide a constructor
        for it because misuse risk outweighs the convenience.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Multiply by 1609.344 and store. The factor is representable to within
        one ULP in binary64 (the exact value is 1609.344 = 50292/31.25 which
        has a non-terminating binary expansion, but the rounded representation
        differs from the exact value by less than 2.3e-13 m per mile).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One MULSD, one MOVSD.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. The constant 1609.344 is compiled in as a literal.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l be a value of type Length
    Set l.si_meters to value multiplied by 1609.344
    Return l
End Process

Process called "length_in_feet" takes value as Float returns Length:
    Let l be a value of type Length
    Set l.si_meters to value multiplied by 0.3048
    Return l
End Process

Process called "length_in_inches" takes value as Float returns Length:
    Let l be a value of type Length
    Set l.si_meters to value multiplied by 0.0254
    Return l
End Process

Process called "length_in_yards" takes value as Float returns Length:
    Let l be a value of type Length
    Set l.si_meters to value multiplied by 0.9144
    Return l
End Process

Process called "length_in_astronomical_units" takes value as Float returns Length:
    @Reasoning:
        The astronomical unit is the IAU 2012 defined value 149597870700 m
        (resolution B2, XXVIII General Assembly, Beijing 2012). Prior to
        that date the AU was a derived quantity tied to the heliocentric
        gravitational constant; the redefinition fixed it as an exact length.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Multiply by 1.495978707e11 and store. The factor exceeds 2^37 so it
        is not representable exactly in binary64, but the rounding error
        (~ 0.5 ULP) is negligible for any practical astronomical use.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One MULSD, one MOVSD.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. The constant exceeds 1e11 m; callers who multiply astronomical
        distances by other astronomical distances may exceed Float range
        and produce infinity, which is the expected IEEE 754 behavior.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l be a value of type Length
    Set l.si_meters to value multiplied by 149597870700.0
    Return l
End Process

Process called "length_in_light_years" takes value as Float returns Length:
    @Reasoning:
        The IAU light-year is defined as the distance light travels in
        vacuum in one Julian year (365.25 days). With c = 299792458 m/s
        (exact since 1983 SI definition of the meter) and a Julian year of
        31557600 s, the light-year equals exactly 9460730472580800 m.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Multiply by 9.4607304725808e15 and store. This value exceeds 2^53
        so the literal carries a rounding error of ~1 ULP relative to the
        exact integer; the resulting Length is accurate to about 1 m per
        light-year, which is below the precision needed for any practical
        astrometric use of the unit.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One MULSD, one MOVSD.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l be a value of type Length
    Set l.si_meters to value multiplied by 9460730472580800.0
    Return l
End Process

Process called "length_in_parsecs" takes value as Float returns Length:
    @Reasoning:
        Per IAU 2015 Resolution B2 (Honolulu), one parsec equals exactly
        (648000 / pi) astronomical units. Numerically this evaluates to
        3.0856775814913673e16 m, the value used here.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Multiply by 3.0856775814913673e16 and store. Like the light-year
        constant the literal exceeds 2^53 and carries rounding error around
        1 ULP.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One MULSD, one MOVSD.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let l be a value of type Length
    Set l.si_meters to value multiplied by 30856775814913676.0
    Return l
End Process

Process called "length_to_meters" takes l as Length returns Float:
    Return l.si_meters
End Process

Process called "length_to_kilometers" takes l as Length returns Float:
    Return l.si_meters divided by 1000.0
End Process

Process called "length_to_centimeters" takes l as Length returns Float:
    Return l.si_meters divided by 0.01
End Process

Process called "length_to_millimeters" takes l as Length returns Float:
    Return l.si_meters divided by 0.001
End Process

Process called "length_to_miles" takes l as Length returns Float:
    Return l.si_meters divided by 1609.344
End Process

Process called "length_to_feet" takes l as Length returns Float:
    Return l.si_meters divided by 0.3048
End Process

Process called "length_to_inches" takes l as Length returns Float:
    Return l.si_meters divided by 0.0254
End Process

Process called "length_to_yards" takes l as Length returns Float:
    Return l.si_meters divided by 0.9144
End Process

Process called "length_to_astronomical_units" takes l as Length returns Float:
    Return l.si_meters divided by 149597870700.0
End Process

Process called "length_to_light_years" takes l as Length returns Float:
    Return l.si_meters divided by 9460730472580800.0
End Process

Process called "length_to_parsecs" takes l as Length returns Float:
    Return l.si_meters divided by 30856775814913676.0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 7 - Length: same-dimension arithmetic
Note: ============================================================================
Note: These operations are defined ONLY between Length-typed values. Attempting
Note: to call length_add with a Mass argument is a compile-time type error
Note: because Mass is a distinct nominal type. This is the core dimensional-
Note: analysis guarantee. The Mars Climate Orbiter would never have crashed
Note: had its impulse data been typed.

Process called "length_add" takes a as Length, b as Length returns Length:
    Let r be a value of type Length
    Set r.si_meters to a.si_meters plus b.si_meters
    Return r
End Process

Process called "length_subtract" takes a as Length, b as Length returns Length:
    Let r be a value of type Length
    Set r.si_meters to a.si_meters minus b.si_meters
    Return r
End Process

Process called "length_scale" takes l as Length, scalar as Float returns Length:
    Let r be a value of type Length
    Set r.si_meters to l.si_meters multiplied by scalar
    Return r
End Process

Process called "length_divide_scalar" takes l as Length, scalar as Float returns Length:
    Let r be a value of type Length
    Set r.si_meters to l.si_meters divided by scalar
    Return r
End Process

Process called "length_negate" takes l as Length returns Length:
    Let r be a value of type Length
    Set r.si_meters to 0.0 minus l.si_meters
    Return r
End Process

Process called "length_equals" takes a as Length, b as Length returns Integer:
    If a.si_meters is equal to b.si_meters:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "length_less_than" takes a as Length, b as Length returns Integer:
    If a.si_meters is less than b.si_meters:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "length_greater_than" takes a as Length, b as Length returns Integer:
    If a.si_meters is greater than b.si_meters:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 8 - Mass: constructors, accessors, arithmetic
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Conversion factors:
Note:   1 g           = 0.001 kg
Note:   1 lb          = 0.45359237 kg (international avoirdupois pound, exact)
Note:   1 slug        = 14.59390294 kg (IEEE 260.1-2004)
Note:   1 solar mass  = 1.98892e30 kg (IAU 2015 nominal solar mass parameter)
Note:   1 planck mass = 2.176434e-8 kg (CODATA 2018)

Process called "mass_in_kilograms" takes value as Float returns Mass:
    @Reasoning:
        Canonical Mass constructor. Kilogram is the SI base unit and so
        receives the identity constructor.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Default-construct Mass and write value to si_kilograms.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One store.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let m be a value of type Mass
    Set m.si_kilograms to value
    Return m
End Process

Process called "mass_in_grams" takes value as Float returns Mass:
    Let m be a value of type Mass
    Set m.si_kilograms to value multiplied by 0.001
    Return m
End Process

Process called "mass_in_pounds" takes value as Float returns Mass:
    Let m be a value of type Mass
    Set m.si_kilograms to value multiplied by 0.45359237
    Return m
End Process

Process called "mass_in_slugs" takes value as Float returns Mass:
    Let m be a value of type Mass
    Set m.si_kilograms to value multiplied by 14.59390294
    Return m
End Process

Process called "mass_in_solar_masses" takes value as Float returns Mass:
    Note: 1 solar mass = 1.98892 * 10^30 kg = 1988920000000000000000000000000 kg
    Let m be a value of type Mass
    Set m.si_kilograms to value multiplied by 1988920000000000000000000000000.0
    Return m
End Process

Process called "mass_in_planck_masses" takes value as Float returns Mass:
    Let m be a value of type Mass
    Set m.si_kilograms to value multiplied by 0.00000002176434
    Return m
End Process

Process called "mass_to_kilograms" takes m as Mass returns Float:
    Return m.si_kilograms
End Process

Process called "mass_to_grams" takes m as Mass returns Float:
    Return m.si_kilograms divided by 0.001
End Process

Process called "mass_to_pounds" takes m as Mass returns Float:
    Return m.si_kilograms divided by 0.45359237
End Process

Process called "mass_to_slugs" takes m as Mass returns Float:
    Return m.si_kilograms divided by 14.59390294
End Process

Process called "mass_to_solar_masses" takes m as Mass returns Float:
    Return m.si_kilograms divided by 1988920000000000000000000000000.0
End Process

Process called "mass_to_planck_masses" takes m as Mass returns Float:
    Return m.si_kilograms divided by 0.00000002176434
End Process

Process called "mass_add" takes a as Mass, b as Mass returns Mass:
    Let r be a value of type Mass
    Set r.si_kilograms to a.si_kilograms plus b.si_kilograms
    Return r
End Process

Process called "mass_subtract" takes a as Mass, b as Mass returns Mass:
    Let r be a value of type Mass
    Set r.si_kilograms to a.si_kilograms minus b.si_kilograms
    Return r
End Process

Process called "mass_scale" takes m as Mass, scalar as Float returns Mass:
    Let r be a value of type Mass
    Set r.si_kilograms to m.si_kilograms multiplied by scalar
    Return r
End Process

Process called "mass_equals" takes a as Mass, b as Mass returns Integer:
    If a.si_kilograms is equal to b.si_kilograms:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 9 - Time: constructors, accessors, arithmetic
Note: ============================================================================
Note: This Time is the physical-quantity time, suitable for force/acceleration/
Note: derivatives. It is INTENTIONALLY separate from calendar Duration in
Note: runtime/services/datetime - mixing wall-clock arithmetic with physics
Note: time is a category error even when both are scalar-Floats internally.
Note: Conversion factors: 1 ms = 0.001 s, 1 us = 0.000001 s, 1 ns = 1e-9 s,
Note: 1 ps = 1e-12 s, 1 fs = 1e-15 s (these are written in code as decimal
Note: literals because the stage1 lexer treats negative exponents on float
Note: literals as separate identifier-plus-negative-integer tokens).

Process called "time_in_seconds" takes value as Float returns Time:
    Let t be a value of type Time
    Set t.si_seconds to value
    Return t
End Process

Process called "time_in_milliseconds" takes value as Float returns Time:
    Let t be a value of type Time
    Set t.si_seconds to value multiplied by 0.001
    Return t
End Process

Process called "time_in_microseconds" takes value as Float returns Time:
    Let t be a value of type Time
    Set t.si_seconds to value multiplied by 0.000001
    Return t
End Process

Process called "time_in_nanoseconds" takes value as Float returns Time:
    Let t be a value of type Time
    Set t.si_seconds to value multiplied by 0.000000001
    Return t
End Process

Process called "time_in_picoseconds" takes value as Float returns Time:
    Let t be a value of type Time
    Set t.si_seconds to value multiplied by 0.000000000001
    Return t
End Process

Process called "time_in_femtoseconds" takes value as Float returns Time:
    Let t be a value of type Time
    Set t.si_seconds to value multiplied by 0.000000000000001
    Return t
End Process

Process called "time_to_seconds" takes t as Time returns Float:
    Return t.si_seconds
End Process

Process called "time_to_milliseconds" takes t as Time returns Float:
    Return t.si_seconds divided by 0.001
End Process

Process called "time_to_microseconds" takes t as Time returns Float:
    Return t.si_seconds divided by 0.000001
End Process

Process called "time_to_nanoseconds" takes t as Time returns Float:
    Return t.si_seconds divided by 0.000000001
End Process

Process called "time_to_picoseconds" takes t as Time returns Float:
    Return t.si_seconds divided by 0.000000000001
End Process

Process called "time_to_femtoseconds" takes t as Time returns Float:
    Return t.si_seconds divided by 0.000000000000001
End Process

Process called "time_add" takes a as Time, b as Time returns Time:
    Let r be a value of type Time
    Set r.si_seconds to a.si_seconds plus b.si_seconds
    Return r
End Process

Process called "time_subtract" takes a as Time, b as Time returns Time:
    Let r be a value of type Time
    Set r.si_seconds to a.si_seconds minus b.si_seconds
    Return r
End Process

Process called "time_scale" takes t as Time, scalar as Float returns Time:
    Let r be a value of type Time
    Set r.si_seconds to t.si_seconds multiplied by scalar
    Return r
End Process

Process called "time_equals" takes a as Time, b as Time returns Integer:
    If a.si_seconds is equal to b.si_seconds:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 10 - Temperature: scale-aware constructors
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Kelvin and Rankine are absolute scales (zero = absolute zero); celsius
Note: and fahrenheit are interval scales (zero is by convention). The
Note: from-celsius and from-fahrenheit constructors apply the offset:
Note:   K = C + 273.15
Note:   K = (F + 459.67) * 5/9
Note:   K = R * 5/9 (R = K * 9/5)

Process called "temperature_in_kelvin" takes value as Float returns Temperature:
    Let t be a value of type Temperature
    Set t.si_kelvin to value
    Return t
End Process

Process called "temperature_in_celsius" takes value as Float returns Temperature:
    @Reasoning:
        Celsius converts to Kelvin via the additive offset 273.15 (defined
        by the 1990 ITS-90 standard, exact). This converts the interval-
        scale celsius value to an absolute-scale kelvin value suitable for
        ratios and gas-law equations.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Add 273.15 to value and store in si_kelvin. The constant 273.15 is
        representable to within 0.5 ULP in binary64.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One ADDSD, one MOVSD.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Sub-zero celsius input produces a kelvin value that is positive
        as long as input > -273.15. Inputs below -273.15 produce negative
        absolute temperatures which are physically meaningless but not
        rejected here - callers are responsible for plausibility checks.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let t be a value of type Temperature
    Set t.si_kelvin to value plus 273.15
    Return t
End Process

Process called "temperature_in_fahrenheit" takes value as Float returns Temperature:
    @Reasoning:
        Fahrenheit to Kelvin: K = (F - 32) * 5/9 + 273.15
        Equivalent and more numerically convenient: K = (F + 459.67) * 5/9.
        We use the latter form because it folds the two offsets into one
        constant and minimizes accumulated rounding error.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Compute (value + 459.67) * 5 / 9 in left-to-right order and store.
        The constant 459.67 is the (rounded) Kelvin equivalent of -459.67 F
        which is absolute zero on the Rankine-derived Fahrenheit scale.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One ADDSD, one MULSD, one DIVSD, one MOVSD.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let t be a value of type Temperature
    Let shifted be value plus 459.67
    Let scaled be shifted multiplied by 5.0
    Set t.si_kelvin to scaled divided by 9.0
    Return t
End Process

Process called "temperature_in_rankine" takes value as Float returns Temperature:
    @Reasoning:
        Rankine to Kelvin: K = R * 5/9. Rankine is an absolute scale
        (zero = absolute zero) using fahrenheit-sized degrees.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Multiply by 5/9 and store in si_kelvin.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One MULSD, one DIVSD, one MOVSD.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let t be a value of type Temperature
    Let scaled be value multiplied by 5.0
    Set t.si_kelvin to scaled divided by 9.0
    Return t
End Process

Process called "temperature_to_kelvin" takes t as Temperature returns Float:
    Return t.si_kelvin
End Process

Process called "temperature_to_celsius" takes t as Temperature returns Float:
    Return t.si_kelvin minus 273.15
End Process

Process called "temperature_to_fahrenheit" takes t as Temperature returns Float:
    Let scaled be t.si_kelvin multiplied by 9.0
    Let in_r be scaled divided by 5.0
    Return in_r minus 459.67
End Process

Process called "temperature_to_rankine" takes t as Temperature returns Float:
    Let scaled be t.si_kelvin multiplied by 9.0
    Return scaled divided by 5.0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 11 - ElectricCurrent, AmountOfSubstance, LuminousIntensity
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "current_in_amperes" takes value as Float returns ElectricCurrent:
    Let c be a value of type ElectricCurrent
    Set c.si_amperes to value
    Return c
End Process

Process called "current_in_milliamperes" takes value as Float returns ElectricCurrent:
    Let c be a value of type ElectricCurrent
    Set c.si_amperes to value multiplied by 0.001
    Return c
End Process

Process called "current_in_microamperes" takes value as Float returns ElectricCurrent:
    Let c be a value of type ElectricCurrent
    Set c.si_amperes to value multiplied by 0.000001
    Return c
End Process

Process called "current_to_amperes" takes c as ElectricCurrent returns Float:
    Return c.si_amperes
End Process

Process called "current_to_milliamperes" takes c as ElectricCurrent returns Float:
    Return c.si_amperes divided by 0.001
End Process

Process called "current_to_microamperes" takes c as ElectricCurrent returns Float:
    Return c.si_amperes divided by 0.000001
End Process

Process called "substance_in_moles" takes value as Float returns AmountOfSubstance:
    Let s be a value of type AmountOfSubstance
    Set s.si_moles to value
    Return s
End Process

Process called "substance_to_moles" takes s as AmountOfSubstance returns Float:
    Return s.si_moles
End Process

Process called "luminous_in_candela" takes value as Float returns LuminousIntensity:
    Let l be a value of type LuminousIntensity
    Set l.si_candela to value
    Return l
End Process

Process called "luminous_to_candela" takes l as LuminousIntensity returns Float:
    Return l.si_candela
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 12 - Angle: constructors, accessors, arithmetic
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Conversion factors:
Note:   1 radian      = 1 radian (SI base)
Note:   1 degree      = pi / 180 radians  (~ 0.01745329251994 rad)
Note:   1 gradian     = pi / 200 radians  (~ 0.01570796326795 rad)
Note:   1 turn        = 2 * pi radians    (~ 6.28318530717959 rad)
Note:   1 arcminute   = 1/60 degree       (~ 0.00029088820867 rad)
Note:   1 arcsecond   = 1/3600 degree     (~ 4.848 microradians)
Note: We hardcode the pi-derived constants to full Float precision rather
Note: than computing them at runtime to keep these constructors branch-free
Note: and dependency-free.

Process called "angle_in_radians" takes value as Float returns Angle:
    Let a be a value of type Angle
    Set a.si_radians to value
    Return a
End Process

Process called "angle_in_degrees" takes value as Float returns Angle:
    Let a be a value of type Angle
    Set a.si_radians to value multiplied by 0.017453292519943295
    Return a
End Process

Process called "angle_in_gradians" takes value as Float returns Angle:
    Let a be a value of type Angle
    Set a.si_radians to value multiplied by 0.015707963267948967
    Return a
End Process

Process called "angle_in_turns" takes value as Float returns Angle:
    Let a be a value of type Angle
    Set a.si_radians to value multiplied by 6.283185307179586
    Return a
End Process

Process called "angle_in_arcminutes" takes value as Float returns Angle:
    Let a be a value of type Angle
    Set a.si_radians to value multiplied by 0.0002908882086657216
    Return a
End Process

Process called "angle_in_arcseconds" takes value as Float returns Angle:
    Let a be a value of type Angle
    Set a.si_radians to value multiplied by 0.000004848136811095360
    Return a
End Process

Process called "angle_to_radians" takes a as Angle returns Float:
    Return a.si_radians
End Process

Process called "angle_to_degrees" takes a as Angle returns Float:
    Return a.si_radians divided by 0.017453292519943295
End Process

Process called "angle_to_gradians" takes a as Angle returns Float:
    Return a.si_radians divided by 0.015707963267948967
End Process

Process called "angle_to_turns" takes a as Angle returns Float:
    Return a.si_radians divided by 6.283185307179586
End Process

Process called "angle_to_arcminutes" takes a as Angle returns Float:
    Return a.si_radians divided by 0.0002908882086657216
End Process

Process called "angle_to_arcseconds" takes a as Angle returns Float:
    Return a.si_radians divided by 0.000004848136811095360
End Process

Process called "angle_add" takes a as Angle, b as Angle returns Angle:
    Let r be a value of type Angle
    Set r.si_radians to a.si_radians plus b.si_radians
    Return r
End Process

Process called "angle_subtract" takes a as Angle, b as Angle returns Angle:
    Let r be a value of type Angle
    Set r.si_radians to a.si_radians minus b.si_radians
    Return r
End Process

Process called "angle_scale" takes a as Angle, scalar as Float returns Angle:
    Let r be a value of type Angle
    Set r.si_radians to a.si_radians multiplied by scalar
    Return r
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 13 - Derived quantities: typed multiplicative constructors
Note: ============================================================================
Note: These procedures express each derived dimension as a product or quotient
Note: of base dimensions. Because each takes typed arguments, a velocity
Note: cannot be accidentally constructed from a Mass and a Time, etc.

Process called "area_from_length_length" takes a as Length, b as Length returns Area:
    @Reasoning:
        Area is the product of two lengths. Taking two Length arguments rather
        than two Floats means the caller cannot accidentally pass a value
        wrapped in some other dimensional type.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Multiply si_meters fields and store in si_square_meters.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One MULSD, one MOVSD.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let r be a value of type Area
    Set r.si_square_meters to a.si_meters multiplied by b.si_meters
    Return r
End Process

Process called "volume_from_area_length" takes a as Area, l as Length returns Volume:
    Let r be a value of type Volume
    Set r.si_cubic_meters to a.si_square_meters multiplied by l.si_meters
    Return r
End Process

Process called "velocity_from_length_and_time" takes l as Length, t as Time returns Velocity:
    @Reasoning:
        Velocity is displacement per unit time. Dividing by Time enforces that
        the divisor is dimensionally a time, not a length or a mass.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Divide si_meters by si_seconds and store in si_meters_per_second.
        Division by zero produces +infinity or NaN per IEEE 754; we do not
        guard against it because callers may legitimately compute limits
        where t -> 0 (e.g. instantaneous-velocity derivations).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One DIVSD, one MOVSD.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. IEEE 754 inf/NaN propagation is the expected response to
        degenerate inputs.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let r be a value of type Velocity
    Set r.si_meters_per_second to l.si_meters divided by t.si_seconds
    Return r
End Process

Process called "velocity_in_meters_per_second" takes value as Float returns Velocity:
    Let v be a value of type Velocity
    Set v.si_meters_per_second to value
    Return v
End Process

Process called "velocity_in_kilometers_per_hour" takes value as Float returns Velocity:
    Let v be a value of type Velocity
    Set v.si_meters_per_second to value divided by 3.6
    Return v
End Process

Process called "velocity_in_miles_per_hour" takes value as Float returns Velocity:
    Let v be a value of type Velocity
    Set v.si_meters_per_second to value multiplied by 0.44704
    Return v
End Process

Process called "velocity_in_knots" takes value as Float returns Velocity:
    Note: 1 knot = 1 nautical mile per hour = 1852 m / 3600 s = 0.5144444... m/s
    Let v be a value of type Velocity
    Set v.si_meters_per_second to value multiplied by 0.5144444444444444
    Return v
End Process

Process called "velocity_speed_of_light" returns Velocity:
    Note: c = 299792458 m/s (exact, 1983 SI definition of the meter)
    Let v be a value of type Velocity
    Set v.si_meters_per_second to 299792458.0
    Return v
End Process

Process called "velocity_to_meters_per_second" takes v as Velocity returns Float:
    Return v.si_meters_per_second
End Process

Process called "velocity_to_kilometers_per_hour" takes v as Velocity returns Float:
    Return v.si_meters_per_second multiplied by 3.6
End Process

Process called "velocity_to_miles_per_hour" takes v as Velocity returns Float:
    Return v.si_meters_per_second divided by 0.44704
End Process

Process called "velocity_to_knots" takes v as Velocity returns Float:
    Return v.si_meters_per_second divided by 0.5144444444444444
End Process

Process called "velocity_add" takes a as Velocity, b as Velocity returns Velocity:
    Let r be a value of type Velocity
    Set r.si_meters_per_second to a.si_meters_per_second plus b.si_meters_per_second
    Return r
End Process

Process called "acceleration_from_velocity_and_time" takes v as Velocity, t as Time returns Acceleration:
    Let r be a value of type Acceleration
    Set r.si_meters_per_second_squared to v.si_meters_per_second divided by t.si_seconds
    Return r
End Process

Process called "acceleration_in_meters_per_second_squared" takes value as Float returns Acceleration:
    Let a be a value of type Acceleration
    Set a.si_meters_per_second_squared to value
    Return a
End Process

Process called "acceleration_in_g" takes value as Float returns Acceleration:
    Note: Standard gravity, g_n = 9.80665 m/s^2 (CGPM 1901, ISO 80000-3:2019)
    Let a be a value of type Acceleration
    Set a.si_meters_per_second_squared to value multiplied by 9.80665
    Return a
End Process

Process called "acceleration_to_meters_per_second_squared" takes a as Acceleration returns Float:
    Return a.si_meters_per_second_squared
End Process

Process called "acceleration_to_g" takes a as Acceleration returns Float:
    Return a.si_meters_per_second_squared divided by 9.80665
End Process

Process called "jerk_from_acceleration_and_time" takes a as Acceleration, t as Time returns Jerk:
    Let r be a value of type Jerk
    Set r.si_meters_per_second_cubed to a.si_meters_per_second_squared divided by t.si_seconds
    Return r
End Process

Process called "force_from_mass_acceleration" takes m as Mass, a as Acceleration returns Force:
    @Reasoning:
        Newton's second law: F = m * a. Taking Mass and Acceleration as
        typed arguments precludes the Mars-Climate-Orbiter failure mode of
        passing a force value (lbf*s) into a function expecting an impulse
        (N*s) - they are different dimensions and would not type-check.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Multiply si_kilograms by si_meters_per_second_squared and store in
        si_newtons.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One MULSD, one MOVSD.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let r be a value of type Force
    Set r.si_newtons to m.si_kilograms multiplied by a.si_meters_per_second_squared
    Return r
End Process

Process called "force_in_newtons" takes value as Float returns Force:
    Let f be a value of type Force
    Set f.si_newtons to value
    Return f
End Process

Process called "force_in_pounds_force" takes value as Float returns Force:
    Note: 1 lbf = 4.4482216152605 N (exact: 1 lbf = 1 lbm * g_n)
    Let f be a value of type Force
    Set f.si_newtons to value multiplied by 4.4482216152605
    Return f
End Process

Process called "force_in_dynes" takes value as Float returns Force:
    Note: 1 dyne = 1e-5 N (CGS unit)
    Let f be a value of type Force
    Set f.si_newtons to value multiplied by 0.00001
    Return f
End Process

Process called "force_to_newtons" takes f as Force returns Float:
    Return f.si_newtons
End Process

Process called "force_to_pounds_force" takes f as Force returns Float:
    Return f.si_newtons divided by 4.4482216152605
End Process

Process called "force_to_dynes" takes f as Force returns Float:
    Return f.si_newtons divided by 0.00001
End Process

Process called "pressure_from_force_and_area" takes f as Force, a as Area returns Pressure:
    Let r be a value of type Pressure
    Set r.si_pascals to f.si_newtons divided by a.si_square_meters
    Return r
End Process

Process called "pressure_in_pascals" takes value as Float returns Pressure:
    Let p be a value of type Pressure
    Set p.si_pascals to value
    Return p
End Process

Process called "pressure_in_bars" takes value as Float returns Pressure:
    Note: 1 bar = 1e5 Pa (exact, by 1982 IUPAC convention)
    Let p be a value of type Pressure
    Set p.si_pascals to value multiplied by 100000.0
    Return p
End Process

Process called "pressure_in_psi" takes value as Float returns Pressure:
    Note: 1 psi = 6894.757293168361 Pa (= 1 lbf / sq.in.)
    Let p be a value of type Pressure
    Set p.si_pascals to value multiplied by 6894.757293168361
    Return p
End Process

Process called "pressure_in_atmospheres" takes value as Float returns Pressure:
    Note: 1 atm = 101325 Pa (exact, by 1954 CGPM definition)
    Let p be a value of type Pressure
    Set p.si_pascals to value multiplied by 101325.0
    Return p
End Process

Process called "pressure_in_mmhg" takes value as Float returns Pressure:
    Note: 1 mmHg = 133.322387415 Pa (manometric pressure of mercury column at 0 C)
    Let p be a value of type Pressure
    Set p.si_pascals to value multiplied by 133.322387415
    Return p
End Process

Process called "pressure_in_torr" takes value as Float returns Pressure:
    Note: 1 torr = 101325 / 760 Pa = 133.32236842105263 Pa
    Let p be a value of type Pressure
    Set p.si_pascals to value multiplied by 133.32236842105263
    Return p
End Process

Process called "pressure_to_pascals" takes p as Pressure returns Float:
    Return p.si_pascals
End Process

Process called "pressure_to_bars" takes p as Pressure returns Float:
    Return p.si_pascals divided by 100000.0
End Process

Process called "pressure_to_psi" takes p as Pressure returns Float:
    Return p.si_pascals divided by 6894.757293168361
End Process

Process called "pressure_to_atmospheres" takes p as Pressure returns Float:
    Return p.si_pascals divided by 101325.0
End Process

Process called "pressure_to_mmhg" takes p as Pressure returns Float:
    Return p.si_pascals divided by 133.322387415
End Process

Process called "pressure_to_torr" takes p as Pressure returns Float:
    Return p.si_pascals divided by 133.32236842105263
End Process

Process called "energy_from_force_and_length" takes f as Force, l as Length returns Energy:
    Let r be a value of type Energy
    Set r.si_joules to f.si_newtons multiplied by l.si_meters
    Return r
End Process

Process called "energy_in_joules" takes value as Float returns Energy:
    Let e be a value of type Energy
    Set e.si_joules to value
    Return e
End Process

Process called "energy_in_kilojoules" takes value as Float returns Energy:
    Let e be a value of type Energy
    Set e.si_joules to value multiplied by 1000.0
    Return e
End Process

Process called "energy_in_megajoules" takes value as Float returns Energy:
    Let e be a value of type Energy
    Set e.si_joules to value multiplied by 1000000.0
    Return e
End Process

Process called "energy_in_gigajoules" takes value as Float returns Energy:
    Let e be a value of type Energy
    Set e.si_joules to value multiplied by 1000000000.0
    Return e
End Process

Process called "energy_in_kilowatt_hours" takes value as Float returns Energy:
    Note: 1 kWh = 3.6e6 J (exact, 1000 W * 3600 s)
    Let e be a value of type Energy
    Set e.si_joules to value multiplied by 3600000.0
    Return e
End Process

Process called "energy_in_btu" takes value as Float returns Energy:
    Note: International Table BTU = 1055.05585262 J (ISO 31-4:1992)
    Let e be a value of type Energy
    Set e.si_joules to value multiplied by 1055.05585262
    Return e
End Process

Process called "energy_in_calories" takes value as Float returns Energy:
    Note: Thermochemical calorie = 4.184 J (exact)
    Let e be a value of type Energy
    Set e.si_joules to value multiplied by 4.184
    Return e
End Process

Process called "energy_in_electron_volts" takes value as Float returns Energy:
    Note: 1 eV = 1.602176634 * 10^-19 J (CODATA 2018, exact by 2019 SI redefinition)
    Note: Encoded as 0.0000000000000000001602176634 to avoid negative-exponent literal.
    Let e be a value of type Energy
    Set e.si_joules to value multiplied by 0.0000000000000000001602176634
    Return e
End Process

Process called "energy_to_joules" takes e as Energy returns Float:
    Return e.si_joules
End Process

Process called "energy_to_kilojoules" takes e as Energy returns Float:
    Return e.si_joules divided by 1000.0
End Process

Process called "energy_to_megajoules" takes e as Energy returns Float:
    Return e.si_joules divided by 1000000.0
End Process

Process called "energy_to_gigajoules" takes e as Energy returns Float:
    Return e.si_joules divided by 1000000000.0
End Process

Process called "energy_to_kilowatt_hours" takes e as Energy returns Float:
    Return e.si_joules divided by 3600000.0
End Process

Process called "energy_to_btu" takes e as Energy returns Float:
    Return e.si_joules divided by 1055.05585262
End Process

Process called "energy_to_calories" takes e as Energy returns Float:
    Return e.si_joules divided by 4.184
End Process

Process called "energy_to_electron_volts" takes e as Energy returns Float:
    Return e.si_joules divided by 0.0000000000000000001602176634
End Process

Process called "power_from_energy_and_time" takes e as Energy, t as Time returns Power:
    Let r be a value of type Power
    Set r.si_watts to e.si_joules divided by t.si_seconds
    Return r
End Process

Process called "power_in_watts" takes value as Float returns Power:
    Let p be a value of type Power
    Set p.si_watts to value
    Return p
End Process

Process called "power_in_kilowatts" takes value as Float returns Power:
    Let p be a value of type Power
    Set p.si_watts to value multiplied by 1000.0
    Return p
End Process

Process called "power_in_megawatts" takes value as Float returns Power:
    Let p be a value of type Power
    Set p.si_watts to value multiplied by 1000000.0
    Return p
End Process

Process called "power_in_gigawatts" takes value as Float returns Power:
    Let p be a value of type Power
    Set p.si_watts to value multiplied by 1000000000.0
    Return p
End Process

Process called "power_in_horsepower" takes value as Float returns Power:
    Note: Mechanical (imperial) horsepower = 745.69987158227022 W (ISO 31-4)
    Let p be a value of type Power
    Set p.si_watts to value multiplied by 745.6998715822702
    Return p
End Process

Process called "power_to_watts" takes p as Power returns Float:
    Return p.si_watts
End Process

Process called "power_to_kilowatts" takes p as Power returns Float:
    Return p.si_watts divided by 1000.0
End Process

Process called "power_to_megawatts" takes p as Power returns Float:
    Return p.si_watts divided by 1000000.0
End Process

Process called "power_to_gigawatts" takes p as Power returns Float:
    Return p.si_watts divided by 1000000000.0
End Process

Process called "power_to_horsepower" takes p as Power returns Float:
    Return p.si_watts divided by 745.6998715822702
End Process

Process called "torque_from_force_and_length" takes f as Force, l as Length returns Torque:
    @Reasoning:
        Torque (moment of force) is Force times the lever arm length. The
        dimensional analysis is identical to Energy (N*m = J), but torque
        is a vector quantity expressing a tendency to rotate while energy
        is a scalar - we keep them as distinct types so a torque cannot be
        accidentally interpreted as an energy budget or vice versa.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Multiply Newton by meter and store in si_newton_meters.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One MULSD, one MOVSD.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let r be a value of type Torque
    Set r.si_newton_meters to f.si_newtons multiplied by l.si_meters
    Return r
End Process

Process called "torque_in_newton_meters" takes value as Float returns Torque:
    Let t be a value of type Torque
    Set t.si_newton_meters to value
    Return t
End Process

Process called "torque_in_pound_feet" takes value as Float returns Torque:
    Note: 1 lbf*ft = 1.3558179483314004 N*m (lbf * 0.3048)
    Let t be a value of type Torque
    Set t.si_newton_meters to value multiplied by 1.3558179483314004
    Return t
End Process

Process called "torque_to_newton_meters" takes t as Torque returns Float:
    Return t.si_newton_meters
End Process

Process called "torque_to_pound_feet" takes t as Torque returns Float:
    Return t.si_newton_meters divided by 1.3558179483314004
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 14 - Electromagnetic derived quantities
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "voltage_from_power_and_current" takes p as Power, c as ElectricCurrent returns Voltage:
    Let r be a value of type Voltage
    Set r.si_volts to p.si_watts divided by c.si_amperes
    Return r
End Process

Process called "voltage_in_volts" takes value as Float returns Voltage:
    Let v be a value of type Voltage
    Set v.si_volts to value
    Return v
End Process

Process called "voltage_in_millivolts" takes value as Float returns Voltage:
    Let v be a value of type Voltage
    Set v.si_volts to value multiplied by 0.001
    Return v
End Process

Process called "voltage_in_kilovolts" takes value as Float returns Voltage:
    Let v be a value of type Voltage
    Set v.si_volts to value multiplied by 1000.0
    Return v
End Process

Process called "voltage_to_volts" takes v as Voltage returns Float:
    Return v.si_volts
End Process

Process called "voltage_to_millivolts" takes v as Voltage returns Float:
    Return v.si_volts divided by 0.001
End Process

Process called "voltage_to_kilovolts" takes v as Voltage returns Float:
    Return v.si_volts divided by 1000.0
End Process

Process called "resistance_from_voltage_and_current" takes v as Voltage, c as ElectricCurrent returns Resistance:
    @Reasoning:
        Ohm's law: R = V / I. Typed arguments enforce that the divisor is a
        current and the dividend is a voltage, preventing the all-too-common
        unit-error of treating a voltage as a current.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Divide si_volts by si_amperes and store in si_ohms.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One DIVSD, one MOVSD.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Zero current yields infinity (open circuit), which is the
        physically meaningful answer.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let r be a value of type Resistance
    Set r.si_ohms to v.si_volts divided by c.si_amperes
    Return r
End Process

Process called "resistance_in_ohms" takes value as Float returns Resistance:
    Let r be a value of type Resistance
    Set r.si_ohms to value
    Return r
End Process

Process called "resistance_in_kilohms" takes value as Float returns Resistance:
    Let r be a value of type Resistance
    Set r.si_ohms to value multiplied by 1000.0
    Return r
End Process

Process called "resistance_in_megohms" takes value as Float returns Resistance:
    Let r be a value of type Resistance
    Set r.si_ohms to value multiplied by 1000000.0
    Return r
End Process

Process called "resistance_to_ohms" takes r as Resistance returns Float:
    Return r.si_ohms
End Process

Process called "resistance_to_kilohms" takes r as Resistance returns Float:
    Return r.si_ohms divided by 1000.0
End Process

Process called "resistance_to_megohms" takes r as Resistance returns Float:
    Return r.si_ohms divided by 1000000.0
End Process

Process called "capacitance_from_charge_and_voltage" takes q as Charge, v as Voltage returns Capacitance:
    Let r be a value of type Capacitance
    Set r.si_farads to q.si_coulombs divided by v.si_volts
    Return r
End Process

Process called "capacitance_in_farads" takes value as Float returns Capacitance:
    Let c be a value of type Capacitance
    Set c.si_farads to value
    Return c
End Process

Process called "capacitance_in_microfarads" takes value as Float returns Capacitance:
    Let c be a value of type Capacitance
    Set c.si_farads to value multiplied by 0.000001
    Return c
End Process

Process called "capacitance_in_nanofarads" takes value as Float returns Capacitance:
    Let c be a value of type Capacitance
    Set c.si_farads to value multiplied by 0.000000001
    Return c
End Process

Process called "capacitance_in_picofarads" takes value as Float returns Capacitance:
    Let c be a value of type Capacitance
    Set c.si_farads to value multiplied by 0.000000000001
    Return c
End Process

Process called "capacitance_to_farads" takes c as Capacitance returns Float:
    Return c.si_farads
End Process

Process called "capacitance_to_microfarads" takes c as Capacitance returns Float:
    Return c.si_farads divided by 0.000001
End Process

Process called "capacitance_to_nanofarads" takes c as Capacitance returns Float:
    Return c.si_farads divided by 0.000000001
End Process

Process called "capacitance_to_picofarads" takes c as Capacitance returns Float:
    Return c.si_farads divided by 0.000000000001
End Process

Process called "inductance_from_voltage_time_current" takes v as Voltage, t as Time, c as ElectricCurrent returns Inductance:
    Let r be a value of type Inductance
    Let numerator be v.si_volts multiplied by t.si_seconds
    Set r.si_henries to numerator divided by c.si_amperes
    Return r
End Process

Process called "inductance_in_henries" takes value as Float returns Inductance:
    Let i be a value of type Inductance
    Set i.si_henries to value
    Return i
End Process

Process called "inductance_in_millihenries" takes value as Float returns Inductance:
    Let i be a value of type Inductance
    Set i.si_henries to value multiplied by 0.001
    Return i
End Process

Process called "inductance_in_microhenries" takes value as Float returns Inductance:
    Let i be a value of type Inductance
    Set i.si_henries to value multiplied by 0.000001
    Return i
End Process

Process called "inductance_to_henries" takes i as Inductance returns Float:
    Return i.si_henries
End Process

Process called "inductance_to_millihenries" takes i as Inductance returns Float:
    Return i.si_henries divided by 0.001
End Process

Process called "inductance_to_microhenries" takes i as Inductance returns Float:
    Return i.si_henries divided by 0.000001
End Process

Process called "charge_from_current_and_time" takes c as ElectricCurrent, t as Time returns Charge:
    Let r be a value of type Charge
    Set r.si_coulombs to c.si_amperes multiplied by t.si_seconds
    Return r
End Process

Process called "charge_in_coulombs" takes value as Float returns Charge:
    Let q be a value of type Charge
    Set q.si_coulombs to value
    Return q
End Process

Process called "charge_to_coulombs" takes q as Charge returns Float:
    Return q.si_coulombs
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 15 - Rotational and oscillatory derived quantities
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "angular_velocity_from_angle_and_time" takes a as Angle, t as Time returns AngularVelocity:
    Let r be a value of type AngularVelocity
    Set r.si_radians_per_second to a.si_radians divided by t.si_seconds
    Return r
End Process

Process called "angular_velocity_in_radians_per_second" takes value as Float returns AngularVelocity:
    Let w be a value of type AngularVelocity
    Set w.si_radians_per_second to value
    Return w
End Process

Process called "angular_velocity_in_degrees_per_second" takes value as Float returns AngularVelocity:
    Let w be a value of type AngularVelocity
    Set w.si_radians_per_second to value multiplied by 0.017453292519943295
    Return w
End Process

Process called "angular_velocity_in_rpm" takes value as Float returns AngularVelocity:
    Note: 1 rpm = 2*pi/60 rad/s = 0.10471975511965977 rad/s
    Let w be a value of type AngularVelocity
    Set w.si_radians_per_second to value multiplied by 0.10471975511965977
    Return w
End Process

Process called "angular_velocity_to_radians_per_second" takes w as AngularVelocity returns Float:
    Return w.si_radians_per_second
End Process

Process called "angular_velocity_to_degrees_per_second" takes w as AngularVelocity returns Float:
    Return w.si_radians_per_second divided by 0.017453292519943295
End Process

Process called "angular_velocity_to_rpm" takes w as AngularVelocity returns Float:
    Return w.si_radians_per_second divided by 0.10471975511965977
End Process

Process called "angular_acceleration_from_angular_velocity_and_time" takes w as AngularVelocity, t as Time returns AngularAcceleration:
    Let r be a value of type AngularAcceleration
    Set r.si_radians_per_second_squared to w.si_radians_per_second divided by t.si_seconds
    Return r
End Process

Process called "angular_acceleration_in_radians_per_second_squared" takes value as Float returns AngularAcceleration:
    Let a be a value of type AngularAcceleration
    Set a.si_radians_per_second_squared to value
    Return a
End Process

Process called "angular_acceleration_to_radians_per_second_squared" takes a as AngularAcceleration returns Float:
    Return a.si_radians_per_second_squared
End Process

Process called "frequency_from_time" takes t as Time returns Frequency:
    @Reasoning:
        Frequency is the reciprocal of period: f = 1 / T. This is exact in
        principle but bears IEEE 754 rounding for non-power-of-two periods.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Divide 1.0 by si_seconds and store in si_hertz.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One DIVSD, one MOVSD.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Period of zero yields infinity (instantaneous), valid IEEE 754.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let r be a value of type Frequency
    Set r.si_hertz to 1.0 divided by t.si_seconds
    Return r
End Process

Process called "frequency_in_hertz" takes value as Float returns Frequency:
    Let f be a value of type Frequency
    Set f.si_hertz to value
    Return f
End Process

Process called "frequency_in_kilohertz" takes value as Float returns Frequency:
    Let f be a value of type Frequency
    Set f.si_hertz to value multiplied by 1000.0
    Return f
End Process

Process called "frequency_in_megahertz" takes value as Float returns Frequency:
    Let f be a value of type Frequency
    Set f.si_hertz to value multiplied by 1000000.0
    Return f
End Process

Process called "frequency_in_gigahertz" takes value as Float returns Frequency:
    Let f be a value of type Frequency
    Set f.si_hertz to value multiplied by 1000000000.0
    Return f
End Process

Process called "frequency_in_terahertz" takes value as Float returns Frequency:
    Let f be a value of type Frequency
    Set f.si_hertz to value multiplied by 1000000000000.0
    Return f
End Process

Process called "frequency_to_hertz" takes f as Frequency returns Float:
    Return f.si_hertz
End Process

Process called "frequency_to_kilohertz" takes f as Frequency returns Float:
    Return f.si_hertz divided by 1000.0
End Process

Process called "frequency_to_megahertz" takes f as Frequency returns Float:
    Return f.si_hertz divided by 1000000.0
End Process

Process called "frequency_to_gigahertz" takes f as Frequency returns Float:
    Return f.si_hertz divided by 1000000000.0
End Process

Process called "frequency_to_terahertz" takes f as Frequency returns Float:
    Return f.si_hertz divided by 1000000000000.0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 16 - Information and data rate
Note: ============================================================================
Note: IEC 60027-2 binary prefixes:
Note:   1 byte     = 8 bits
Note:   1 KiB      = 1024 bytes  = 8192 bits
Note:   1 MiB      = 1024 KiB    = 1048576 bytes
Note:   1 GiB      = 1024 MiB
Note:   1 TiB      = 1024 GiB
Note:   1 PiB      = 1024 TiB
Note: We store in bits and convert at the accessor boundary to keep one
Note: canonical unit.

Process called "information_in_bits" takes value as Float returns Information:
    Let i be a value of type Information
    Set i.si_bits to value
    Return i
End Process

Process called "information_in_bytes" takes value as Float returns Information:
    Let i be a value of type Information
    Set i.si_bits to value multiplied by 8.0
    Return i
End Process

Process called "information_in_kibibytes" takes value as Float returns Information:
    Let i be a value of type Information
    Set i.si_bits to value multiplied by 8192.0
    Return i
End Process

Process called "information_in_mebibytes" takes value as Float returns Information:
    Let i be a value of type Information
    Set i.si_bits to value multiplied by 8388608.0
    Return i
End Process

Process called "information_in_gibibytes" takes value as Float returns Information:
    Let i be a value of type Information
    Set i.si_bits to value multiplied by 8589934592.0
    Return i
End Process

Process called "information_in_tebibytes" takes value as Float returns Information:
    Let i be a value of type Information
    Set i.si_bits to value multiplied by 8796093022208.0
    Return i
End Process

Process called "information_in_pebibytes" takes value as Float returns Information:
    Let i be a value of type Information
    Set i.si_bits to value multiplied by 9007199254740992.0
    Return i
End Process

Process called "information_to_bits" takes i as Information returns Float:
    Return i.si_bits
End Process

Process called "information_to_bytes" takes i as Information returns Float:
    Return i.si_bits divided by 8.0
End Process

Process called "information_to_kibibytes" takes i as Information returns Float:
    Return i.si_bits divided by 8192.0
End Process

Process called "information_to_mebibytes" takes i as Information returns Float:
    Return i.si_bits divided by 8388608.0
End Process

Process called "information_to_gibibytes" takes i as Information returns Float:
    Return i.si_bits divided by 8589934592.0
End Process

Process called "information_to_tebibytes" takes i as Information returns Float:
    Return i.si_bits divided by 8796093022208.0
End Process

Process called "information_to_pebibytes" takes i as Information returns Float:
    Return i.si_bits divided by 9007199254740992.0
End Process

Process called "data_rate_from_information_and_time" takes i as Information, t as Time returns DataRate:
    Let r be a value of type DataRate
    Set r.si_bits_per_second to i.si_bits divided by t.si_seconds
    Return r
End Process

Process called "data_rate_in_bits_per_second" takes value as Float returns DataRate:
    Let d be a value of type DataRate
    Set d.si_bits_per_second to value
    Return d
End Process

Process called "data_rate_in_kilobits_per_second" takes value as Float returns DataRate:
    Note: Per ITU-T convention, network k = 1000 (decimal), not 1024.
    Let d be a value of type DataRate
    Set d.si_bits_per_second to value multiplied by 1000.0
    Return d
End Process

Process called "data_rate_in_megabits_per_second" takes value as Float returns DataRate:
    Let d be a value of type DataRate
    Set d.si_bits_per_second to value multiplied by 1000000.0
    Return d
End Process

Process called "data_rate_in_gigabits_per_second" takes value as Float returns DataRate:
    Let d be a value of type DataRate
    Set d.si_bits_per_second to value multiplied by 1000000000.0
    Return d
End Process

Process called "data_rate_to_bits_per_second" takes d as DataRate returns Float:
    Return d.si_bits_per_second
End Process

Process called "data_rate_to_kilobits_per_second" takes d as DataRate returns Float:
    Return d.si_bits_per_second divided by 1000.0
End Process

Process called "data_rate_to_megabits_per_second" takes d as DataRate returns Float:
    Return d.si_bits_per_second divided by 1000000.0
End Process

Process called "data_rate_to_gigabits_per_second" takes d as DataRate returns Float:
    Return d.si_bits_per_second divided by 1000000000.0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 17 - Cross-conversion helpers (kinetic energy and similar)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Some derived quantities require non-trivial combinations. We expose a
Note: handful as named procedures.

Process called "kinetic_energy_from_mass_and_velocity" takes m as Mass, v as Velocity returns Energy:
    @Reasoning:
        E_k = (1/2) m v^2. Newtonian, non-relativistic. For v near c the
        Lorentz factor must be applied; this procedure intentionally does
        not perform that check because the caller's choice of regime is a
        physics-not-types question.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        v^2 = v.si_meters_per_second * v.si_meters_per_second.
        E = 0.5 * m.si_kilograms * v_squared.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Two MULSD, one MOVSD.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Overflow possible for very large m*v^2 (~10^308); IEEE 754
        infinity is the standard response.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let v_squared be v.si_meters_per_second multiplied by v.si_meters_per_second
    Let m_v2 be m.si_kilograms multiplied by v_squared
    Let r be a value of type Energy
    Set r.si_joules to m_v2 multiplied by 0.5
    Return r
End Process

Process called "potential_energy_from_mass_height_gravity" takes m as Mass, h as Length, g as Acceleration returns Energy:
    Note: U = m g h.
    Let mg be m.si_kilograms multiplied by g.si_meters_per_second_squared
    Let mgh be mg multiplied by h.si_meters
    Let r be a value of type Energy
    Set r.si_joules to mgh
    Return r
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 18 - Dimensional ratios that yield Float (dimensionless)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Dividing two same-dimension quantities yields a dimensionless scalar.
Note: For instance, two lengths divided produce a dimensionless ratio,
Note: which we return as a bare Float.

Process called "length_ratio" takes a as Length, b as Length returns Float:
    Return a.si_meters divided by b.si_meters
End Process

Process called "mass_ratio" takes a as Mass, b as Mass returns Float:
    Return a.si_kilograms divided by b.si_kilograms
End Process

Process called "time_ratio" takes a as Time, b as Time returns Float:
    Return a.si_seconds divided by b.si_seconds
End Process

Process called "velocity_ratio" takes a as Velocity, b as Velocity returns Float:
    Return a.si_meters_per_second divided by b.si_meters_per_second
End Process

Process called "energy_ratio" takes a as Energy, b as Energy returns Float:
    Return a.si_joules divided by b.si_joules
End Process
